to play an important role in the creation of the state. He describes how a community of relatively high status and free from persecution under the British Raj left the recently independent India for fear of losing status, only to encounter bias and prejudice in their new country. In 1960, a decision made by the religious authorities to ban the Bene Israel from marrying other Jews on the grounds that they were not "pure Jews" set in motion a civil rights struggle between the Indian community and the religious authority with far-reaching implications. After a drawn-out struggle, and under pressure from both the government and the people, the Bene Israel were declared acceptable for marriage. A detailed look at how one immigrant community fought to maintain their place within a religion and a society, From India to Israel raises important questions about the state of Israel and its earliest struggles to absorb the diversity in its midst.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBene-IsraelxHistory. 0aFreedom of religionzIndiaxHistory. 0aFreedom of religionzIsraelxHistory. 0aJewsxIdentityxHistory. 0aJewszIndiaxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359701340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773597013423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773597013/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles